# Edit ~/.bashrc

Only execute this part of the plan when the user asks to "set bashrc", "update bashrc" or "configure bashrc" and exit. Do not execute the rest of the plan.

1. We will be applying edits to this file: `/home/coder/.bashrc`
2. Navigate to `/home/coder` directory and run `ls`. See the name of the `.code-workspace` file. If and only if the name has a `-conda` suffix then in `/home/coder/.bashrc` (for example if the file name is `wkstn-cu13.1-conda.code-workspace`) replace the definition of the `__bash_prompt()` function with the following:

```bash
__bash_prompt() {
    local userpart='`export XIT=$? \
        && [ ! -z "${GITHUB_USER:-}" ] && echo -n "\[\033[1;32m\]@${GITHUB_USER:-} " || echo -n "\[\033[1;32m\]\u " \
        && [ "$XIT" -ne "0" ] && echo -n "\[\033[1;31m\]➜" || echo -n "\[\033[0m\]➜"`'
    local gitbranch='`\
        if [ "$(git config --get devcontainers-theme.hide-status 2>/dev/null)" != 1 ] && [ "$(git config --get codespaces-theme.hide-status 2>/dev/null)" != 1 ]; then \
            export BRANCH=$(git --no-optional-locks symbolic-ref --short HEAD 2>/dev/null || git --no-optional-locks rev-parse --short HEAD 2>/dev/null); \
            if [ "${BRANCH}" != "" ]; then \
                echo -n "\[\033[1;36m\](\[\033[1;31m\]${BRANCH}" \
                && if [ "$(git config --get devcontainers-theme.show-dirty 2>/dev/null)" = 1 ] && \
                    git --no-optional-locks ls-files --error-unmatch -m --directory --no-empty-directory -o --exclude-standard ":/*" > /dev/null 2>&1; then \
                        echo -n " \[\033[1;33m\]✗"; \
                fi \
                && echo -n "\[\033[1;36m\]) "; \
            fi; \
        fi`'
    local red='\[\033[1;31m\]'
    local removecolor='\[\033[0m\]'
    PS1="${CONDA_PROMPT_MODIFIER:-}${userpart} ${red}\w ${gitbranch}${removecolor}\$ "
    unset -f __bash_prompt
}
```

3. If the workspace name did have a `-conda` suffix, also export this variable (only if not already) at the end of the `~/.bashrc` file we are editing. Make sure to leave empty lines before and after this blob

```bash
# Set ls colors
export LS_COLORS=$LS_COLORS:'di=34;42:';
```

4. Now regardless of the name of the workspace file, export these variables (only if not already done) at the end of the `~/.bashrc` file we are editing. Leave one empty line before and after this blob

```bash
alias nvccdump='nvcc --compiler-options -dM -E -x cu - < /dev/null'
alias gppdump='echo | g++ -dM -E -x c++ -'
alias nvcppdump='echo | nvc++ -dM -E -x c++ -'
alias set-native='export CUDAARCHS=NATIVE'
alias restart-sccache='devcontainer-utils-start-sccache --kill-all'
```

# Setup signing key

Only execute this part of the plan when the user asks to "setup signing key", "setup gh key" or "update signing key" and exit. Do not execute the rest of the plan.

1. Navigate to `/home/coder` and check if a `.ssh` folder containing `id_ed25519` and `id_ed25519.pub` files. If so, skip to step 3. Otherwise, if the folder doesn't exist or doesn't contain `id_ed25519` files, go to step 2
2. Look inside `/home/coder/cudf/python/cudf/build` and its subdirectories to find an existing `.ssh` folder. Hint: It may be under `/home/coder/cudf/python/cudf/build/*devcontainer*`. Copy the `.ssh` folder to `/home/coder` as is. If you can't find the `.ssh` folder here, pause and ask me to tell you what to do next.
3. Now once we have the `/home/coder/.ssh` folder ready, execute the following script in a terminal:

```bash
# Start the ssh-agent in the background
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"

# Add your SSH private key to the ssh-agent.
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519

# Display the generated key
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

# tell git about signing key
git config --global gpg.format ssh
git config --global user.signingkey ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
```

